  "prompt": "So, can a sentence begin with the word \"so\"?",
  "response": "Yes, a sentence can absolutely begin with the word \"so.\" While it was once considered informal or conversational to start a sentence with \"so,\" it has become widely accepted in both spoken and written English. It is often used to introduce or connect ideas, summarize, or emphasize a point. For example:\n\n- \"So, what should we do next?\"\n- \"So, the project was completed ahead of schedule.\"\n- \"So, let me explain why this is important.\"\n\nStarting a sentence with \"so\" is now seen as natural and effective in many contexts, though its use should still align with the tone and style of your writing or speech.",
